body:
Using Verilator 5.006 on Ubuntu 20.04, and trying to verilate the following code
```
always begin    
fork
    begin: u_check_1
        #delay_1;
        #1 disable u_check_2;
        fork
            begin: l_check_1
                #delay_2;
                #1 disable l_check_2;
            end
            begin: l_check_2
                @(posedge clk);
                #1 disable l_check_1;
            end
        join 
    end
    
    begin: u_check_2
        @(posedge clk);
        #1 disable u_check_1;
    end
join
end 
```
I get the following error messages. 
```
%Error: ../../ver/th/test.v:119:12: disable isn't underneath a begin with name: 'u_check_2'
  119 |         #1 disable u_check_2;
      |            ^~~~~~~
%Error: ../../ver/th/test.v:123:20: disable isn't underneath a begin with name: 'l_check_2'
  123 |                 #1 disable l_check_2;
      |                    ^~~~~~~
%Error: ../../ver/th/test.v:127:20: disable isn't underneath a begin with name: 'l_check_1'
  127 |                 #1 disable l_check_1;
      |                    ^~~~~~~
%Error: ../../ver/th/test.v:134:12: disable isn't underneath a begin with name: 'u_check_1'
  134 |         #1 disable u_check_1;

```
Which seems to point out that Verilator only accept `disable` statements when the target named block is the current named block. I think that this is  incorrect. I looked at the LRM but I could not find anything suggesting that it should be restricted this way.
